(A)

Rationale: The glutathione S-transferases constitute a large multi-gene family with numerous isoenzymes (well over a dozen cytosolic classes in mammals), not merely “two GSTs.”

All other statements accurately describe the family:
(B) Catalytic activity requires the co-factor glutathione; 
(C) GSTs detoxify a wide array of electrophilic intermediates; 
(D) In the majority of cases the GSH conjugates formed are less toxic than the parent compound (though exceptions exist); 
(E) Most GST isoforms are soluble enzymes located in the cytosol.
